Answer:<<<api>>>: BufferedReader.readLine
<<<code>>>: public static String getTextFromFile(File file) {
    StringBuilder stringBuilder = new StringBuilder();
    try {
        BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
        String line;
        while ((line = bufferedReader.readLine()) != null) {
            stringBuilder.append(line).append("\n");
        }
        bufferedReader.close();
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
    return stringBuilder.toString();
}
<<<explanation>>>: This method reads the content of a text file and returns it as a String. The content is appended to the StringBuilder line by line, separated by a newline character. The resulting String can be displayed in a TextView.

A: You can use BufferedReader.readLine() in a loop until it returns null, which means there are no more lines to read. Here is an example:
public static List<String> getLinesFromConsole() {
    List<String> lines = new ArrayList<>();
    try {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        String line;
        while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
            lines.add(line);
        }
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
    return lines;
}

This will read lines from the console until the user enters an empty line (just presses Enter without typing anything), at which point readLine() will return null.

A: You can use Scanner class to read lines from the console. It will continue to read until it encounters an end of stream.
Here is an example:
public static List<String> getLinesFromConsole() {
    List<String> lines = new ArrayList<>();
    try (Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in)) {
        while (scanner.hasNextLine()) {
            lines.add(scanner.nextLine());
        }
    }
    return lines;
}

This code will read lines from the console until there are no more lines to read. The lines are added to a list which is then returned.

